summary.seg: This manuscript, probably copied in the second half of the 14th century, is a Sticherarion, a liturgical book containing the stichera idiomela (hymns with their own melodies, rather than conforming to a standard type) sung at orthros and vespers (morning and evening services).

It is divided into a Menaion, containing hymns for the feasts of the fixed calendar beginning on 1 September, and two components covering sections of the mobile calendar based on the date of Easter. These are the Triodion, covering Lent and Holy Week, and the Pentekostarion, covering the period from Easter to the feast of All Saints. Confusingly, the Triodion here begins with a heading indicating the beginning of the Pentekostarion (f. 193r). There is also a series of stichera prosomoia (hymns set to standard melodies) for Lent, and the sequence of Eothina anastasima (the eleven morning hymns of the Resurrection) attributed to the Emperor Leo VI (866-912), another normal component of the Sticherarion, together with a few individual hymns. Bound at the beginning and end of the manuscript, probably as endleaves from a previous binding, are leaves taken from two other hymn-books of similar date, one from the beginning of another Sticherarion. All are accompanied by musical notation of the "Round" type, in use in the later centuries of the Byzantine period.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers [i-ii] + [iii] + 1-299 + [iv-v], in Arabic numerals, in pencil, recto, upper right. This foliation initially began by including the early endleaf f. [iii] as the first folio. This sequence is marked until f. 18r, but its numbers have later been struck out and replaced by those of the present sequence. Numbers of this cancelled sequence continue to appear intermittently thereafter, sometimes with errors.
supportDesc.condition: Serious pest damage runs through the whole manuscript. There is a tear across f. 174. Extensive brown stains appear in the gutter on ff. 279v-299v. The paper has become soft in places. There is water staining and areas of dirt.

binding.p: 18th-century full leather binding over couched-laminate boards, with plain pastedowns. There is decorative gold tooling on the spine and blind tooling on the edges. The title Hymni in dies festos is tooled in gold on a red label on the spine, and the classmark appears there on patches. The title Ψαλτηκα is written on the tail-edge.
binding.condition: Both endbands are partly detached and the headband is split.

physDesc.accMat: A note on content is pasted to the modern endleaf f. [ii] verso: Hymni in dies festos cum notis musicis. ex dono Genadii Monachi.

collation.p: The main body of the manuscript consists of 39 quires, of which one is a single leaf, one a binion, one a ternion and the rest are quaternia.

list.item: Quire 218-1 ff. 159-165 The seventh folio has been lost, with loss of text.
Quire 254-1 ff. 190-192 The last folio has been cancelled, without loss of text.
Quire 391 f. 297 Only the first three folios of this quire survive

collation.signatures: There are quire signatures in Arabic numerals, in pencil, on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower right. They survive on Quires 1-8, 22-39. The signature for Quire 6 is misplaced, appearing one folio too late.

layoutDesc.layout: ff. 1r-297r A single column of 17 lines. 150-160 100
f. 297v A single column of 15 lines. 139 95

handNote.p: ff. 1r-297r were copied by Hand B in upright mixed minuscule script, in black ink, with consistent letter size. Diacritics and abbreviations are not used.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, middle comma and full stop.

Headings are written in the same style, with diacritics and abbreviations, in red ink. Breathings are round. There is decorative use of the double dot and accentuation of all lengths of nomina sacra. Accents are sometimes joined to abbreviations.
The opening heading is written in epigraphic display majuscule script, in red ink (f. 1r).

f. 297v was copied by Hand C in upright mixed minuscule script, in black ink, with consistent letter size. Accents and breathings are used only in headings. Punctuation used includes the middle point and full stop.

physDesc.musicNotation: The text is supplied with Round notation.

decoDesc.decoNote: Sections of the text are preceded by horizontal headpieces in red ink (ff. 1r, 108r, 193r) or a thin band of ornament outlined in black ink with red infill.
Hymns on ff. 1r-297r begin with minor initials in red ink.
Hymns on f. 297v begin with minor initials in black ink.
A large cross-shaped plaited deoration in black ink, with red and yellow infill, appears after the end of a section on f. 174r.

additions.p: As part of the original production of the manuscript, liturgical notes have been added in the margins, and some have been added by later hands. The hand responsible for the note on f. [iii] recto has also added notes to ff. 58v and 174r.

A note on f. 297r records the donation of the manuscript by the monk kyr Gennadios to the Monastery of the Pantokrator on Mount Athos: Τὸ παρὸν στιχεράριον ἔδοσαν ὁ ἐν μοναχοῖς κῦρ Γεννάδιος· εἰς τὴν σεβασμίαν καὶ ἱερὰν μονὴν τοῦ Παντοκρατορος καὶ Σωτῆρος Χριστοῦ τὴν ἁγίω ὄρει τοῦ Ἄθωνος. To this another hand has added a curse on any who remove it from the monastery: καὶ ὁ ἀποξενῶσας αὐτῶ ἐκ τῆς αὐτῆς μονῆς ἐχέτω· τὸν Παντοκράτορα αντίδικον.

history.origin: The manuscript was probably copied in the later 14th century, as suggested by the style of script and musical notation.
